The Cement Company of Northern Nigeria (CCNN) or Sokoto Cement has posted a revenue of N31.7billion, representing about N11.85bn increase from the N19.5bn it posted in 2017. The company also posted a profit after tax of N5.86bn in 2018 as against N2.91bn it posted in 2017. Speaking at the 40th annual general meeting (AGM) of the company for the 2018 financial year held in Abuja  the Chairman, CCNN, Abdulsamad Rabiu, described the 2018 financial period as impressive for the company following a successful merger with Kalambaina Cement. He described the profit sfter that figures as the highest in the history of the company. Also at the AGM, the shareholders of the company approved the payment of N5.25bn as dividend for the 2018 financial period under review. This translates into a dividend payout of 40 kobo per share. Also the approved dividend of N5.25bn is also an increase of N3.68bn or 235 percent over the N1.57bn which the company paid in the 2017 financial period. According to Alh. Rabiu, “the company recorded its highest domestic exports sale during the year. This was facilitated by the additional output from the enlarged entity. “In 2019, we hope to have the full combined capacity of the two entities. With the new capacity, CCNN is now the dominant player in its home market of North West Africa” he said. Cement Company of Northern Nigeria Plc: Strategies hold long term payoffs Sokoto Cement records N1.92bn profit after tax Dangote Cement to earn $700m forex from terminals Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin